explanation:
For determining whether the if-block in OS_CountSemDelete is dead code you must know (a) whether the condition (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) can ever be true and (b) whether the operations inside that block have externally observable effects. Each listed symbol is needed for that analysis:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The callee that produces the initial return_code. You must inspect its implementation/behavior to know if it can return OS_SUCCESS for any sem_id and thus make the if-body reachable.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: These are direct callees used by OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the call graph). Their behavior determines the conditions/logic and side effects inside OS_ObjectIdGetById that lead to different return values; needed to establish reachability of the if-block and any side effects performed even on failure paths.
- OS_CountSemDelete_Impl: The primary operation performed inside the if-block. You must examine it to determine whether it has external effects (state changes, resource release, logging, etc.) whose removal would change program behaviour — if it has no such effects, it might be dead.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Called by OS_CountSemDelete_Impl (per the graph). Its behavior may contribute to side effects or to the result of the delete implementation; include to judge whether the delete implementation has observable effects.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: Called after the Impl call to "complete the operation via the common routine". FinalizeDelete may perform transaction finalization and notifications; you must inspect it to determine external effects that would be lost if the whole if-block were removed.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish, OS_NotifyEvent: Direct callees of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete. They represent observable side effects (transaction completion, event/notification delivery). Their presence/absence is critical to deciding whether removing the if-block alters system behaviour.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Macros/enumerations used to call OS_ObjectIdGetById. Needed to understand call semantics and any special-case behavior of GetById depending on lock/mode/type parameters.
- OS_SUCCESS: The symbolic return-code compared in the if-condition. You must know its value and semantics to reason about the comparison and reachability.
- OS_object_token_t: The token type passed into the object-id routines; its structure may carry state or ownership semantics (and may be modified by callee functions). You must inspect its definition to see whether token construction/modification constitutes observable behaviour (affects other objects) or is purely local.

These symbols together let the analyst determine (1) whether the conditional body is ever executed and (2) whether the body performs externally observable operations whose removal would change program behaviour — the two key aspects needed to decide if the code is dead under MISRA's rule.
